  "informal_statement": "Erdos asked whether a finite set A of complex numbers is determined by the multiset of sums of its k-element subsets. The multiplicative analogue -- is A determined by the multiset of products of its k-subsets? -- is FALSE, by a counterexample of Steinerberger: there exist distinct finite A, B in Finset Complex of equal cardinality with the same multiset of 3-subset products (prodMultiset A 3 = prodMultiset B 3). This is a companion counterexample to the multiplicative analogue, not a resolution of Erdos #494's original sum-based question.",
  "informal_proof_idea": "Let omega be a primitive cube root of unity. Take A = {1, omega, omega^2, 2} and B = omega*A (A != B, witnessed by 2 in A but 2 not in B). Key lemma: scaling every element of a Finset by a scalar c with c^k=1 leaves the multiset of k-subset products unchanged (each k-subset product picks up c^k = 1). Applied with c = omega, k = 3 (omega^3 = 1), this gives prodMultiset A 3 = prodMultiset B 3.",
  "formal_statement_pp": "theorem erdos_494_product : ∃ (A B : Finset ℂ), A.card = B.card ∧ prodMultiset A 3 = prodMultiset B 3 ∧ A ≠ B",
  "proof_body_path": "lean/MathCorpus/Frontier/Erdos/Erdos494Product.lean",
